keywords = {Smart cities, Street lighting optimization, Internet of Things, IoT, TOPSIS multicriteria analysis, City lighting optimization},
abstract = {Devices have been getting smaller, smarter, and more energy efficient, leading to our smart computing era. Smart cities are transforming our everyday lives through the integration of their core services. A major part of the power consumed by cities is used by street illumination. The conventional illumination method consumes high power and rapidly depletes luminaire lifetime. In this chapter, a Centralized Eco-Friendly Role Assignment Scheme (CEFRAS) has been proposed for smart city street illumination considering requirements such as luminaire type, lighting duration, and zone. System modeling with simulation of the lighting applications facilitates testing various kinds of luminaires in a very large-scale environment. Investigations on performance metrics such as illumination level, power consumption, and luminaire lifetime were performed on the (i) conventional, (ii) static, and (iii) dynamic CEFRAS. The dynamic-CEFRAS in comparison to the static-CEFRAS and conventional method is shown to increase the luminaire lifetime by 25.94% and 33.94%, respectively. The power consumption of the luminaires is minimized by 7.31% and 8.18% by the dynamic-CEFRAS in comparison to static-CEFRAS and the conventional method. Thus, the dynamic-CEFRAS increases the overall lifetime of the luminaires and minimizes the overall power consumption.}
